            {
                "sectionId": "phys-t001-s002",
                "type": "text",
                "title": "Handout: Newton's Laws",
                "text": "KEY POINTS:\n1. Inertia (1st Law): Objects resist change in motion.\n2. F=ma (2nd Law): Force depends on mass and acceleration.\n3. Action-Reaction (3rd Law): Forces act in equal opposite pairs.\n\nDEFINITIONS:\n- Force: A push or pull.\n- Mass: Amount of matter.\n- Inertia: Resistance to change."
            },
            {
                "sectionId": "phys-t001-s003",
                "type": "introduction",
                "title": "The Law of Inertia",
                "text": "An object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by an unbalanced force."
            },
            {
                "sectionId": "phys-t001-s005",
                "type": "introduction",
                "title": "Action and Reaction",
                "text": "For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction. This means that in every interaction, there is a pair of forces acting on the two interacting objects. The size of the forces on the first object equals the size of the force on the second object."
            },
            {
                "sectionId": "phys-t001-s005",
                "type": "concept_helper",
                "title": "Example",
                "text": "When you sit on a chair, your body exerts a downward force on the chair and the chair exerts an upward force on your body."
            },
            {
                "sectionId": "phys-t001-s006",
                "type": "real_world",
                "title": "Rocket Launches",
                "text": "Rockets move forward by expelling gas backward at high speed. This means the rocket exerts a large backward force on the gas in the combustion chamber, and the gas therefore exerts a large forward reaction force on the rocket."
            },
            {
                "sectionId": "phys-t001-s006",
                "type": "real_world",
                "title": "Walking",
                "text": "When you walk, you push the ground backward, and the reaction force of the ground pushes you forward!"
            }
        ],
